    "sub_topic": "Calculation of the Bohr radius in hydrogen atom",
    "message_1": "Calculate the Bohr radius in a hydrogen atom if the mass of the electron is 9.10938356 × 10^-31 kg and the mass of the proton is 1.6726219 × 10^-27 kg. (Assuming hydrogen atom has one proton and one electron)",
    "message_2": "To calculate the Bohr radius in a hydrogen atom, we can use the formula:\n\nBohr radius (a₀) = (4πε₀ħ²) / (m_e * e²)\n\nwhere:\nε₀ = vacuum permittivity = 8.85418782 × 10^-12 C²/(N·m²)\nħ = reduced Planck constant = 1.0545718 × 10^-34 J·s\nm_e = mass of the electron = 9.10938356 × 10^-31 kg\ne = elementary charge = 1.60217662 × 10^-19 C\n\nPlugging in the values, we get:\n\na₀ = (4π * 8.85418782 × 10^-12 * (1.0545718 × 10^-34)²) / (9.10938356 × 10^-31 * (1.60217662 × 10^-19)²)\n\na₀ = (4π * 8.85418782 × 10^-12 * 1.11245471 × 10^-68) / (9.10938356 × 10^-31 * 2.56985061 × 10^-38)\n\na₀ = (3.14159265 * 9.8696044 × 10^-12 * 1.11245471 × 10^-68) / (9.10938356 × 10^-31 * 2.56985061 × 10^-38)\n\na₀ = (3.14159265 * 9.8696044 × 10^-12 * 1.11245471 × 10^-68) / (2.3478385 × 10^-68)\n\na₀ = 5.29177211 × 10^-11 m\n\nSo, the Bohr radius in a hydrogen atom is approximately 5.29177211 × 10^-11 meters."
